<div id="review_2688484565" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2688484565" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/118558-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1277521087p2/118558.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2688484565?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/118558-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/118558-sarah?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/118558-sarah?shelf=historical">historical</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2688484565" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17415016464239251272">An interesting departure from the usual Brother Cadfael books, as this one could hardly be called a mystery at all, and instead is mostly a straight historical novel. There is a murder, but it is barely relevant to the plot, nor is it Brother Cadfael&apos;s job to solve it.<br/><br/>Instead, Cadfael accompanies Brother Mark (now a deacon to Bishop Roger de Clinton) on a trip into Wales, and the two wind up in the middle of a fight between Welsh brothers, one of whom has sought the services of Irish Dane mercen</span>
  <span id="freeText17415016464239251272" style="display:none">An interesting departure from the usual Brother Cadfael books, as this one could hardly be called a mystery at all, and instead is mostly a straight historical novel. There is a murder, but it is barely relevant to the plot, nor is it Brother Cadfael's job to solve it.<br /><br />Instead, Cadfael accompanies Brother Mark (now a deacon to Bishop Roger de Clinton) on a trip into Wales, and the two wind up in the middle of a fight between Welsh brothers, one of whom has sought the services of Irish Dane mercenaries. <br /><br />I'm quite fond of Mark, and so it was nice to have him featured in a book again, adventuring along with Cadfael.<br /><br />As always, the author brings excellent historical research skills into play, and peoples her book with fascinating characters, some historical, some not. Also as always, her world is a kinder, gentler place, where even many of those who do wrong do so for the best of reasons. I marvel again and again that a series set in the middle ages is one that always features goodness, kindness, and mercy. I often find these books a comfort.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17415016464239251272" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


