<div id="review_3705920265" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3705920265" />
    <a title="Leonide Martin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2579244-leonide-martin"><img alt="Leonide Martin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1544815904p2/2579244.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3705920265?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leonide Martin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leonide Martin" href="/user/show/2579244-leonide-martin">Leonide Martin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3705920265" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14431477684927646053">Brother Cadfael ventures into the wider world far from his monastery into Wales, the Kingdom of Gwynedd where he was born. He accompanies Brother Mark as translator on church business and soon becomes involved in the business of kings and princes. Set amidst verdant meadows and dark misty forests, the mystery of the Welsh permeates the atmosphere, and it is a delight to read about their customs vividly described. Richly drawn characters abound in Peters&apos; characteristically lyrical prose, and a n</span>
  <span id="freeText14431477684927646053" style="display:none">Brother Cadfael ventures into the wider world far from his monastery into Wales, the Kingdom of Gwynedd where he was born. He accompanies Brother Mark as translator on church business and soon becomes involved in the business of kings and princes. Set amidst verdant meadows and dark misty forests, the mystery of the Welsh permeates the atmosphere, and it is a delight to read about their customs vividly described. Richly drawn characters abound in Peters' characteristically lyrical prose, and a nicely complex plot involves a political murder, two princely brothers pitted against each other, a willful Welsh girl determined to marry on her own terms against her father's intentions, and a set of mercenary Danes from Dublin with refreshingly good humor. A satisfying story arc brings several twists and a bit of poetic justice, with the ending readers will ardently desire. This 18th book in the consistently engaging Cadfael series is now my favorite! </span>
  <a data-text-id="14431477684927646053" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


