  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_649910053" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/649910053" />
    <a title="Valerie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1798996-valerie"><img alt="Valerie" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/649910053?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Valerie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Valerie" href="/user/show/1798996-valerie">Valerie</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer649910053" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12131566264990080532">The &apos;summer&apos; in the title is the summer of 1144. The &apos;Danes&apos; in the story are Danes mostly in name: most of them were born in the Danish Kingdom of Dublin, and are mostly Irish through the maternal line. Linguistically, they were most probably generally polyglots, with Latin and/or Danish as a lingua franca.<br/><br/>Though some members of the society hire out as Vikings, most probably stay at home and live more or less the same sort of life as their neighbors on Great Britain proper, and in Denmark, with</span>
  <span id="freeText12131566264990080532" style="display:none">The 'summer' in the title is the summer of 1144. The 'Danes' in the story are Danes mostly in name: most of them were born in the Danish Kingdom of Dublin, and are mostly Irish through the maternal line. Linguistically, they were most probably generally polyglots, with Latin and/or Danish as a lingua franca.<br /><br />Though some members of the society hire out as Vikings, most probably stay at home and live more or less the same sort of life as their neighbors on Great Britain proper, and in Denmark, with which they still had strong cultural and political ties. The Danelaw was established in the ninth century. After the formation of an area where the Danes could settle as citizens north of the Severn and Thames, most if not all raiding by Vikings stopped. The Danes who'd settled in Britain began appealing with the Danish monarchs to put an end to raids from their former neighbors, and were often enough successful to reduce the fear of raids.<br /><br />By the time of this book, the residents of the Danish kingdom of Dublin were not in the habit of raiding in Britain, especially in Wales. Like many peoples who live near the sea, the Welsh had learned to be able to melt into the hills, and leave little or nothing behind for raiders to rob them of. <br /><br />The Irish Danes in this book are quite clearly hirelings. But not necessarily unquestioning hirelings. They're hired by the Welsh prince Cadwaladr to act as his agents to enforce a peace with his brother Owain Gwynedd. It's purely a cash deal, as far as the Danes are concerned. They have no loyalty toward Cadwaladr, nor any trust in him. What they have is a contract with him, and one they have little faith in.<br /><br />Brother Cadfael gets involved in this as a translator for Brother Mark (his apprentice aforetimes), who is sent with greetings and gifts to try to smooth over problems in Church politics. <br /><br />As others have said, this isn't much of a mystery. The map at the front is a map of north Wales, and it might be useful for the reader to have a bibliography to check out the historical background. How, one wonders, did the native Irish respond to the influx of thousands of Danes? <br /><br />But the murders (Cadwaladr's exile and dispossession was originally on account of his ordering the murder of another prince), while not in the foreground in the story, are not irrelevant. And the part Cadfael plays in the story is not just that of onlooker, even in the sense of a witness. Not only is he an effective translator between the Welsh and the Danes (and a respected one, because of his history as a mariner), but he's also a guarantor in the peace negotiations and hostage exchanges. As is Brother Mark. These Danes are Christian, and respect the role of the Church as neutral arbiters. The girl Heledd, the inconvenient daughter of a Welsh canon under a reforming Norman rule, is probably safe enough as a hostage, even without clerical companions. She's obviously worth a considerable ransom, which Owain will pay if nobody else does--but her father and promised husband would probably chip in as well. And Cadwaladr will probably be forced to pay some of the score, as well, since it's 'his' Danes who've captured the girl. But one or two clerics in the mix make her position essentially unassailable. And as heralds and negotiators, you can't beat the clerics. They may have little control over the final decisions, but they have a part in the councils, nevertheless.<br /><br />One thing that struck me as more than a little ambiguous is that while the custom of ultimogeniture is common currency among the Welsh populace, it seems to have become more than a little shaky among the nobles. I gather that Owain, for example, is his father's oldest son. So in traditional Welsh practice, he would have been given his share in the kingdom as soon as he reached his majority--and then the younger Cadwaladr would have received the lion's share at their father's death. It may be this historical discontinuity that caused so much conflict between princely brothers in Wales for many generations.<br /><br />I should say that I wish the matter HAD been brought off in somewhat stiff and formal commerce. Unfortunately, too many young hotheads and too many obstinate old loyalists get involved, and several more people get killed before the story reaches its end.<br /><br />One of the things that makes these stories more humane than we, looking backward, would anticipate is a want of hurry. Even urgent matters spend quite a bit of time in discussions and negotiations. So Brother Mark's original argument that the trip into Wales would take less than 10 days is more a reflection of his own sanguine temperament than any kind of realistic estimate--though of course he wasn't to know that the Danish complication would ensue.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12131566264990080532" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

