<div id="review_1235338095" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1235338095" />
    <a title="Anne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42321-anne"><img alt="Anne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1388463861p2/42321.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1235338095?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anne" href="/user/show/42321-anne">Anne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1235338095" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8262205727502359131">I knew I was eventually going to hit a dud if I kept reading straight through the series. I actually started this one ages ago, and then realized that I had skipped the one before it...which was a relief, because <i>The Summer of the Danes</i> isn&apos;t particularly interesting. There was a murder, but not one that Cadfael had any part in solving, and there were extended passages that didn&apos;t involve Cadfael at all, which doesn&apos;t really interest me. But this was still fairly enjoyable, as these things go; I</span>
  <span id="freeText8262205727502359131" style="display:none">I knew I was eventually going to hit a dud if I kept reading straight through the series. I actually started this one ages ago, and then realized that I had skipped the one before it...which was a relief, because <i>The Summer of the Danes</i> isn't particularly interesting. There was a murder, but not one that Cadfael had any part in solving, and there were extended passages that didn't involve Cadfael at all, which doesn't really interest me. But this was still fairly enjoyable, as these things go; I enjoyed the descriptions of the lush Welsh countryside, and it was nice to experience a different group of medieval people, if amusing to read that the Danes of the Kingdom of Dublin were coming to invade Wales. And it wouldn't be an Ellis Peters mystery without one woman who is smarter than everybody else and takes matters into her own hands--in this case, Heledd, whose father was sending her to Bangor to be married so that he could be a priest without the evidence of his former non-celibate state. It wasn't very subtly done, and I knew where it was headed before anybody else did, but still refreshing, given how man-heavy this book is (and the series, to be honest, what with monks and soldiers and priests and everything).<br /><br />All in all, a weak entry, but certainly not unreadable. I think the next one may be <i>Brother Cadfael's Penance</i>, which intrigues me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8262205727502359131" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


